tional canon, can provide an interesting perspective to reinterpret the literature of the Imperial Age and to get a deeper understanding of the Roman legal mind and of ancient imagery in general. This collection of essays seeks to address the Declamationes Minores from different points of view. Not only does it analyse the specific features of the text as a schoolbook, but it also tries to highlight the contiguity of fictitious speeches with the literary tradition and the legal and philosophical culture of the time. The volume is a useful tool to explore little-known texts, which nevertheless constitute an effective access point to the imagery of the Imperial Age.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Italian.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aBildlichkeit. 0aDeklamation. 0aQuintilian. 0aRhetorik. 4aBildlichkeit. 4aDeklamation. 4aQuintilian. 4aRhetorik. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aDeclamation.  aQuintilian.  aimagery.  arhetoric.1 aCasamento, Alfredo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasamento, Alfredo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDimatteo, Giuseppe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrapinger, Gernot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLentano, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMal-Maeder, Danielle van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMal-Maeder, Danielle van, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOppliger, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasetti, Lucia , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPasetti, Lucia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPingoud, Julien